{\plain \fs24 \b INFERNO CANTO 05}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 1-3.}{\plain \fs24   A descent again marks a border, this time between the Limbus and the second Circle \softline
(see }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . IV.13).  Singleton (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.1) argues that the presence here of Minos in \softline
judgment indicates that 'real hell' begins only now, that Limbo is 'marginal.'  It is true, however, \softline
that the Limbus is inside the gate of hell.  Not only does 'real hell' begin there, it in a sense \softline
begins with those who are held outside the gate, the neutrals.  They are so pusillanimous that \softline
they are not even allowed 'a proper burial,' as it were.  One may not even say, as some have, that \softline
only with the second Circle do we begin to witness actual punishment being meted out for past \softline
sins, since the neutrals are indeed tormented by stinging insects as a fit punishment for their \softline
feckless conduct (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.65-66).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 4-5.}{\plain \fs24   Padoan (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.4) argues that the present tense of the verbs in this tercet \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i (sta}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i ringhia}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i essamina}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i giudica}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i manda}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i avvinghia}{\plain \fs24 ) reflects the continuous condition of Minos's \softline
behavior.  In fact }{\plain \fs24 \i all}{\plain \fs24  the verbs in the passage describing Minos's judgment, vv. 4-15, are in the \softline
present, as Dante leaves little doubt but that he wants his readers to imagine themselves -- unless \softline
a life of good conduct and God's grace combine to gain a better end -- coming before that \softline
judgment in the future.  This is the everlasting present of the moment of damnation, occurring, \softline
the text would make us feel, even as we read.  For a study of the historical present in the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Commedia}{\plain \fs24 , with attention (pp. 266-68) to this passage, see Edoardo Sanguineti ("Dante, \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i praesens historicum}{\plain \fs24 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i Lettere Italiane}{\plain \fs24  10 [1958]), pp. 263-87.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Dante fairly often portrays infernal monsters and characters as having bestial traits.  For \softline
this particular one, canine vociferation, see also Cerberus (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . VI.43), Plutus (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . VII.43), \softline
Hecuba (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXX.20), Bocca degli Abati (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXXII.105; }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXXII.108); Brutus and Cassius \softline
in }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  XXXIV (described as barking retrospectively at }{\plain \fs24 \i Par}{\plain \fs24 . VI.74).  See discussion in \softline
Barbara Spaggiari, "Antecedenti e modelli tipologici nella letteratura in lingua d'o{\f2 \'56}l," in }{\plain \fs24 \i I \softline
"monstra" nell'"Inferno" dantesco: tradizione e simbologie}{\plain \fs24  (Spoleto: Centro italiano di studi \softline
sull'alto medioevo, 1997), p. 112.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab For the conflation here in the figure of Minos of the roles of Minos and of Rhadamanthus \softline
in Virgil's underworld, see Edward Moore, }{\plain \fs24 \i Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 , First Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i Scripture and \softline
Classical Authors in Dante}{\plain \fs24  (Oxford: Clarendon, 1969 [1896]), pp. 183-84; the texts are found at \softline
Aeneid VI.432-433 and VI.566-569.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 6.}{\plain \fs24   Even the precise way that Minos winds his tail about himself is a subject in dispute.  \softline
Does he flap it back and forth as many times as he wishes to indicate the appropriate circle?  Or \softline
does he wind it like a vine around a tree?  See Mazzoni, "Il canto V dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno,}{\plain \fs24 " }{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura Dantis \softline
Romana: Letture degli anni 1973-76}{\plain \fs24  (Rome: Bonacci, 1977), pp. 104-5, for a brief summary of \softline
the debate and reasons to prefer the second hypothesis.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 7.}{\plain \fs24   Sinners are 'ill-begotten' in that their end is this, eternal damnation, because of their \softline
sins (and not because their procreation in itself so fated them).  Padoan (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.7) \softline
points out that Dante himself is later described as 'bene nato' (well born) -- }{\plain \fs24 \i Par}{\plain \fs24 . V.115.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 8.}{\plain \fs24   See Raymond Benoit, "}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V," }{\plain \fs24 \i The Explicator}{\plain \fs24  41, 3 (1983), p. 2.  Dante presents \softline
Minos as a parody of a confessor meting out penance to a sinner.  The word }{\plain \fs24 \i confessa}{\plain \fs24  marks the \softline
beginning of this canto's concern with confession, which will be parodied again when Dante 
'confesses' Francesca (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.118-120).  For now we are perhaps meant to ruminate on the \softline
perversity of sinners.  In the world above they were offered, through this office of the Church, \softline
the possibility of confession and remission of sins.  We may infer that those sinners whom we \softline
find in Hell probably did not avail themselves of their great opportunity.  (We never hear the \softline
word 'confession' on the lips of any of them except for Guido da Montefeltro [}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXVII.83].  \softline
And he, having confessed and become a friar, then sins again and is condemned.  His second \softline
[and vain] confession is made, too late, to Dante.)  This moment offers a brief but cogent vision \softline
of human perversity: in their lives all those whom we see in hell had the opportunity to be rid of \softline
their sins by owning up to them in confession.  They apparently did not do so.  Here, in hell, \softline
what is the very first thing that they do?  They make full disclosure of their sins... to Minos.  \softline
Dante has apparently conflated the general function of Minos as judge of the dead in general \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i Aen}{\plain \fs24 . VI.432) and the role of Rhadamanthus as judge of the damned in particular (}{\plain \fs24 \i Aen}{\plain \fs24 . VI.566-569).  For the most recent discussion see Ignazio Baldelli, }{\plain \fs24 \i Dante e Francesca}{\plain \fs24  (Ravenna: Longo, \softline
1999), pp. 5-6.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 9-12.}{\plain \fs24   The mechanical nature of Minos's judgment -- he is a judge who renders judgment \softline
with his tail, not his head -- underlines the lack of authority of the demons in hell: Minos is \softline
merely doing God's work.  Hell is presented as a perfectly functioning bureaucracy.  If some of \softline
Satan's minions are at times rebellious (e.g., the rebel angels in }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . IX, the winged demons in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XXI-XXIII), they are so in vain.  Hell, too, is a part of God's kingdom.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 17.}{\plain \fs24   Once the narrated action of Dante's descent continues (it had been suspended at v. 3), \softline
the tense moves back to the past definite: 'Minos }{\plain \fs24 \i said}{\plain \fs24 .'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 18-19.}{\plain \fs24   Minos, seeing a rarity, to say the least -- a living man before him at the entrance \softline
to hell -- steals a moment from his incessant judgment to offer this warning.  How kindly are his \softline
intentions?  Most commentators seem to think he is the most 'humane' of the infernal demons, \softline
and even courteous to Dante.  However, and as Padoan points out (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.19), his \softline
calling into question, albeit indirectly, the competence of Virgil as guide ('beware... whom you \softline
trust'), is evidently meant to unsettle Dante.  He would obviously prefer not to have such visitors.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 20.}{\plain \fs24   Commentators customarily note that here Dante builds his line out of two sources: \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  VI.126: 'Facilis descensus Averno' (the }{\plain \fs24 \i descent}{\plain \fs24  to the underworld is easy [but not the \softline
return from there]); Matthew 7:13: 'spatiosa via est, quae ducit ad perditionem' (broad is the way \softline
that leads to perdition).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 21.}{\plain \fs24   The adverb }{\plain \fs24 \i pur}{\plain \fs24  in Virgil's response can be variously understood: as 'vainly' (with the \softline
sense of the Latin }{\plain \fs24 \i frustra}{\plain \fs24 ); as 'indeed' (in the sense of 'why do you persist in?'); as 'also' \softline
(reflecting Charon's similar shouting at }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.84).  Our translation has tried to accommodate the \softline
first two possibilities.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 22-24.}{\plain \fs24   Virgil obviously understands that Minos's words were meant to scare Dante off \softline
(and perhaps he also understands the implicit insult to himself contained in them).  For the \softline
repetition here of the exact same verses (23 and 24) used to quell Charon's rebellious desires see \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.95-96 and the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.95-96.  It seems clear that Virgil would not have used them \softline
again had they not been efficacious the first time, that is, had Charon not relented and rowed 
Dante across.  See the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.136.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 25.}{\plain \fs24   Here the present tense is an example of the 'historical' (or 'vivid') present.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 26-33.}{\plain \fs24   The 'hellscape' that is established by the sounds in the darkness (once again \softline
Dante's eyes need to adjust to the deepening shadows) mates well with the sin of lust: darkness, \softline
passionate winds in conflict that bear their victims in unceasing agitation.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \tab 28-30.}{\plain \fs24   The dark and tempestuous 'hellscape' is a fit background for the sin of lust, \softline
carried out in darkness (at least in the common imagining) amidst the storms of passion.  For a \softline
passage that Dante surely knew and which might have had some effect on his shaping of this \softline
scene, see II Peter 2:10-22, the Apostle Peter's denunciation of the lustful.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 28.}{\plain \fs24   It has become fashionable to speak of Dante's use of 'synaesthesia,' the blending of \softline
different sense impressions (see, e.g., Glauco Cambon, "Synaesthesia in the }{\plain \fs24 \i Divine Comedy}{\plain \fs24 ," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24  88 [1970], pp. 3-5).  The term, however, was coined some 500 years later in \softline
literary history.  Dante would perhaps have referred to the trope rather as 'catachresis,' a daring, \softline
even 'improper,' comparison.  See Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i Il Virgilio dantesco: tragedia nella "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24   \softline
(Florence: Olschki, 1983), pp. 66-67.  And see }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  I.60 for a prior example.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 34.}{\plain \fs24   One of the most debated verses in this canto because of the words }{\plain \fs24 \i la ruina}{\plain \fs24  (literally, \softline
'the ruin').  What precisely do they mean?  Two attempts at evaluation of the commentary \softline
tradition are available, the first by Letterio Cassata, "Tre }{\plain \fs24 \i cruces}{\plain \fs24  dantesche: I. La }{\plain \fs24 \i ruina}{\plain \fs24  dei \softline
lussuriosi," }{\plain \fs24 \i Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24  48 (1971), pp. 5-14; the second, still more complete, by Nicol{\f2 \'62} \softline
Mineo (ED.1973.4, pp. 1056-57).  Mineo points out that there have been six identifiable schools \softline
of interpretation for the meaning of }{\plain \fs24 \i la ruina}{\plain \fs24 .  Unfortunately, there are severe problems \softline
associated with all of them.  Many American and some Italian students of the problem have been \softline
drawn to Singleton's solution (comms. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XII.32 and XII.36-45): Dante suppresses the \softline
meaning of the noun here only to reveal it at }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  XII.32-41, where }{\plain \fs24 \i questa ruina}{\plain \fs24  (verse 32) \softline
refers to the crack in the wall of hell made by the earthquake that accompanied Christ's \softline
crucifixion.  The resultant explanation is so attractive that even many of those who doubt its \softline
literal applicability do not wish to jettison it.  However, it does remain extremely dubious, as \softline
many rightly point out, that Dante would, for the only time in his poem, place the 'antecedent' \softline
necessary to a word's clear literal sense seven cantos after its first appearance.  A grammatical \softline
approach, however, yields still other difficulties.  Who are these people who are arriving 'before \softline
the ruin'?  Are they those who are being driven on the wind in the preceding tercet \softline
(grammatically the most probable reading)?  If that is true, Dante would at least seem to be \softline
contradicting what he will shortly say (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.44-45), namely that the sinners in this circle have \softline
no hope of any change in their condition.  However, what he says there is only that their plight \softline
will never be ameliorated -- a phrasing that might allow for its aggravation, as we would be \softline
witnessing here.  Others, most trenchantly Padoan (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.34), attempt a difficult \softline
argument: the antecedent for the suffering souls in this verse is not in the preceding line, but all \softline
the way back at v. 13: the }{\plain \fs24 \i molte}{\plain \fs24  (many shades) who assemble for the judgment of Minos.  The \softline
result of this interpretation is, as is the case for Singleton's, welcome but unlikely: we have a \softline
'flashback,' as it were, to what happens when the }{\plain \fs24 \i newly}{\plain \fs24  arrived souls (not the ones we have just \softline
been observing) first reach this depth.  And so that solution, too, seems dubious on grammatical 
grounds.  If one, like Mazzoni ("Il canto V dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno,}{\plain \fs24 " }{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura Dantis Romana: Letture degli \softline
anni 1973-76}{\plain \fs24  [Rome: Bonacci, 1977]), pp. 106-8, lets the proximity of grammatical antecedents \softline
have its due weight, one not only thinks that the antecedent of the subject of the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i giungono}{\plain \fs24  is \softline
the }{\plain \fs24 \i li spirti}{\plain \fs24  or }{\plain \fs24 \i li}{\plain \fs24  in the preceding tercet, but that the antecedent of the noun }{\plain \fs24 \i ruina}{\plain \fs24  is the noun \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i bufera}{\plain \fs24  (the hellish squall) in that tercet.  And then, again following Mazzoni, one argues that the \softline
meaning here is not 'ruin,' but the secondary meaning of the word, 'fury, violence.'  One \softline
immediately sees, however, the problem with this solution as well -- Mazzoni is forced to argue \softline
for the same position embraced by Padoan: the action described is that which occurs when the \softline
sinners }{\plain \fs24 \i first}{\plain \fs24  reach this circle (immediately after vv. 13-15), and not that which is habitual and \softline
indeed eternal (vv. 25-33).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Petrocchi (}{\plain \fs24 \i La Commedia secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24 ), pp. 80-81, discusses (and \softline
firmly rejects) the late and decidedly inadmissible reading }{\plain \fs24 \i deventi}{\plain \fs24  [= 'di venti'] }{\plain \fs24 \i la ruina}{\plain \fs24 .\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab The position of a translator who does not have a clear idea of what the original means is \softline
an impossible one.  We chose the path taken by Mazzoni, translating }{\plain \fs24 \i ruina}{\plain \fs24  as 'violence,' before \softline
we consulted his work.  The main reason for doing so is grammatical: all the verb tenses of this \softline
scene that describe the actions or reactions of the sinners are in the present (vv. 25-27; 29-36).  \softline
Thus it seems incorrect to attempt to mark a temporal shift in the action that is not reflected in \softline
the text.  If the tense of the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i giungono}{\plain \fs24  were past instead of present, Mazzoni's solution would \softline
seem optimal.  But there is no instance of a single variant of the verb in the manuscript tradition.  \softline
Thus, as things stand, there seems to be no optimal solution.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 39.}{\plain \fs24   For a probable source for this line see Mazzoni (}{\plain \fs24 \i Il canto VI dell'"Inferno"}{\plain \fs24  in }{\plain \fs24 \i Nuove \softline
letture dantesche}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Le Monnier, 1967]), p. 13, n. 2; "Il canto V dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno,}{\plain \fs24 " }{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura \softline
Dantis Romana: Letture degli anni 1973-76}{\plain \fs24  (Rome: Bonacci, 1977), pp. 108-9: the }{\plain \fs24 \i Tresor}{\plain \fs24  of \softline
Brunetto Latini (II.20), in the chapter on chastity: 'On doit contrester au desirier de delit; car ki \softline
se laisse vaincre, }{\plain \fs24 \i la raison remaint sous le desirier}{\plain \fs24 ....  Par quoi on se doit estudiier }{\plain \fs24 \i que raisons \softline
soit sor la concupiscence}{\plain \fs24 , en tel maniere que l'un et l'autre desirent de bien faire.'  And then, \softline
further along (II.41): 'Et non chastes }{\plain \fs24 \i est cil ki sousmet soi mesmes au delit...}{\plain \fs24 ' (Mazzoni's italics).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 40-49.}{\plain \fs24   The first two similes of the canto (and see the third one, }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.82-85) associate \softline
the lustful with birds, a natural association given their condition, driven by the wind, and one in \softline
accord with the view that lust is the property of beings less than human, and indeed frequently of \softline
birds.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 40-43.}{\plain \fs24   The first vast group of the 'ordinary' lovers (T. S. Eliot's typist and house agent's \softline
clerk in the }{\plain \fs24 \i Waste Land}{\plain \fs24 , vv. 222-248, would eventually be assigned here, one imagines) is \softline
compared to a flock of starlings, with their ragged, darting, sky-covering flight on a winter's day.  \softline
For the Virgilian source, see }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  VI.311-312.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 46-49.}{\plain \fs24   The group in the second simile of the canto is more select, the 'stars' of lustful \softline
living.  Where the starlings are as though without individual identities, the 'masses' of the lustful, \softline
as it were, each of these has a particularity and a certain fame, and is thus worthy of being \softline
treated as exemplary.  (For a discussion of exemplary literature in the middle ages see Carlo \softline
Delcorno, }{\plain \fs24 \i Exemplum e letteratura tra medioevo e rinascimento}{\plain \fs24  (Bologna: Il Mulino, 1989, with \softline
special attention to Dante, pp. 195-227.)  Padoan (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.47), on the other hand, \softline
suggests that this second group is distinguished from the first on moral grounds, since they all 
died by their own hand or at the hand of others, and are as a result more heavily punished.  The \softline
evidence for such a view does not seem present in the text.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab For the cranes see Virgil, }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  X.264-266 as well as Statius, }{\plain \fs24 \i Thebaid}{\plain \fs24  V.11-16.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab The rhyme words }{\plain \fs24 \i lai}{\plain \fs24  and }{\plain \fs24 \i guai}{\plain \fs24  suggest a relationship between the French tradition of love \softline
songs (Padoan, comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.46) and its Italian equivalent.  The cranes are imagined as \softline
singing their sad songs of love much as these sinners are presented as drawing sighs of love-sickness, their 'poetry,' as it were.  For }{\plain \fs24 \i lai}{\plain \fs24  as a term used by the Proven{\f1\u231\'e7}al poets for the laments \softline
of amorous birds see Ferdinando Neri, "La voce }{\plain \fs24 \i lai}{\plain \fs24  nei testi italiani," }{\plain \fs24 \i Atti della Reale Accademia \softline
delle Scienze di Torino, classe di scienze morali, storiche e filologiche}{\plain \fs24  72 (1937), pp. 105-19.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 58-67.}{\plain \fs24   This is the second important 'catalogue' that we find in }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24 .  The first was the \softline
forty identified inhabitants of Limbo (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . IV.102 -- at the end of that note).  In the \softline
circle of lust we find these seven identified sinners and two more: Francesca and Paolo, who \softline
bring the total to nine.  As Curtius argued quite some time ago, given the importance for Dante \softline
of the number nine (the 'number' of his beloved Beatrice), it seems likely that these nine souls \softline
who died for love are associated with her by opposition (Ernst Robert Curtius, }{\plain \fs24 \i European \softline
Literature and the Latin Middle Ages}{\plain \fs24 , tr. W. R. Trask [New York: Harper & Row, 1963 (1948)], \softline
p. 369).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab It is also notable that Dante's catalogues are unlike (and pronouncedly so in this case) \softline
later humanist catalogues of the famous, which thrive on additions, in display of the most arrant \softline
'erudition': }{\plain \fs24 \i the more the better}{\plain \fs24  seems to be the motto of such writers.  Dante, on the other hand, \softline
frequently sculpts his groupings to a purpose.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab One of the insistent poetic }{\plain \fs24 \i topoi}{\plain \fs24  that we find in medieval writers -- and certainly in Dante \softline
-- is that of }{\plain \fs24 \i translatio}{\plain \fs24 .  This is the notion that certain ideas or institutions have their major \softline
manifestations in movement through historical time and space.  The two most usually deployed \softline
examples of this }{\plain \fs24 \i topos}{\plain \fs24  are }{\plain \fs24 \i translatio imperii}{\plain \fs24  (the movement of imperial greatness from Troy to \softline
Rome to 'new Rome' -- wherever that may be in a given patriotic writer's imagination [in Dante's \softline
case the empireless Rome of his own day]) and }{\plain \fs24 \i translatio studii}{\plain \fs24  (the devlopment of serious \softline
intellectual pursuit from its birth in Athens, to its rebirth in Rome, to its new home [Paris, \softline
according to some, in Dante's day]).  It is perhaps useful to think of Dante's catalogues as \softline
reflecting a similar sense of history, of movement through time and space.  In this one we have \softline
three triads: Semiramis, Dido, Cleopatra: lustful queens of the African coast; Helen, Achilles, \softline
Paris: Greek and Trojan lovers whose lusts brought down a kingdom; Tristan; Francesca, Paolo: \softline
a man caught up in destructive passion in King Mark's court in Cornwall, as we move into \softline
Europe and toward the present; and, finally, lovers from the recent past in Rimini, here in Italy.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 58.}{\plain \fs24   Semiramis was the legendary queen of Assyria (Dante has confused the name of her \softline
capital, Babylon, forthat of the Egyptian city, and thus misplaced her realm). She was supposed \softline
to have legalized incest in order to carry out her sexual liaison with her son.  For more about \softline
Semiramis, see Irene Samuel, "Semiramis in the Middle Age: The History of a Legend," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Medievalia et Humanistica}{\plain \fs24  2 (1944), pp. 32-44; see also Marianne Shapiro, "Semiramis in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V," }{\plain \fs24 \i Romance Notes}{\plain \fs24  16 (1975), pp. 455-56.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 61-62.}{\plain \fs24   Dante's use of periphrasis (circumlocution) represents one of his favored \softline
'teaching techniques,' in which he (generally, but certainly not always) offers his readers fairly \softline
easy problems to solve.  There is not, it seems reasonable to believe, a single commentator (or 
student?) who has ever got this one 'wrong.'  Use of periphrasis has a second effect: it tends to \softline
emphasize the importance of the person or thing so presented.  The 'Dido' that we scribble in our \softline
margins stands out from the page, partly because it is we who have supplied the name.  That \softline
Dido is the quintessential presence in this 'flock' is underlined by }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno }{\plain \fs24 V.85, where she is the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i only}{\plain \fs24  named presence in it, having previously been alluded to only indirectly.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab For consideration of the similarity of Dante's treatment of Dido here to that found \softline
previously in one of the }{\plain \fs24 \i rime petrose}{\plain \fs24  ("Cos{\f2 \'58} nel mio parlar," vv. 35-43) see Lino Pertile, "Il \softline
modo di Paolo," in }{\plain \fs24 \i Miscellanea di studi offerta dall'Universit{\f2 \'42} di Urbino a Claudio Varese per i \softline
suoi novantanni}{\plain \fs24 , ed. Giorgio Cerboni Baiardi (Manziana [Rome]: Vecchiarelli Editore, 2001),  p. \softline
630.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 61.}{\plain \fs24   Dido's presence here frequently upsets readers who think that she ought to be found \softline
in canto XIII, since she committed suicide.  It is clear that Dante thinks of the psychology of sin \softline
with a certain sophistication, isolating the impulse, the deeper motive, that drives our actions \softline
from the actions themselves.  In Dido's case this is her uncontrolled desire for Aeneas.  She does \softline
not kill herself from despair (as do the suicides in the thirteenth canto), but rather to give \softline
expression to her need for her lover -- or so Dante would seem to have believed.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 62.}{\plain \fs24   Virgil's similar one-line description of Dido's 'infidelity' occurs at }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  IV.552.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 63.}{\plain \fs24   For Dante's knowledge that Cleopatra committed suicide by having an asp bite her, \softline
see }{\plain \fs24 \i Par}{\plain \fs24 . VI.76-78.  And see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno }{\plain \fs24 V.61 for a discussion of that other famous \softline
suicide, Dido, also placed }{\plain \fs24 \i here}{\plain \fs24  for her wantonness rather than relegated to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  XIII for \softline
having committed suicide.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 65.}{\plain \fs24   It is important to remember that Dante, Greekless, had not read Homer, who only \softline
became available in Latin translation much later in the fourteenth century.  His Achilles is not \softline
the hero of the }{\plain \fs24 \i Iliad}{\plain \fs24  known to some of us, but the warrior-lover portrayed by Statius and others.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 67.}{\plain \fs24   For }{\plain \fs24 \i mille}{\plain \fs24  (one thousand) here and elsewhere in the poem see Baldelli, }{\plain \fs24 \i Dante e \softline
Francesca}{\plain \fs24  (Ravenna: Longo, 1999), p. 25n.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 69-72.  di nostra vita}{\plain \fs24 .  The echo of the first line of the poem (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . I.1) is probably not \softline
coincidental.  Dante was lost 'midway in the journey of our life' and, we will later learn, some of \softline
his most besetting problems arose from misplaced affection.  He was, indeed, near death as a \softline
result of his transgressions.  The repetition of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i smarrito}{\plain \fs24  to describe Dante's distraught \softline
condition also recalls the first tercet of the poem (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . I.3).  Here we can see an emerging pattern \softline
in his re-use of key words from previous contexts in order to enhance the significance of a \softline
current situation in the poem.  See also }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  II.63-64, where the words }{\plain \fs24 \i cammin}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i paura}{\plain \fs24 , and \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i smarrito}{\plain \fs24  join to reflect, looking backward, upon the terrifying situation in which the protagonist \softline
found himself at the poem's opening (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . I.1-6).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 71.}{\plain \fs24   Dante refers to the great figures of the olden days with strikingly anachronistic \softline
terms, the medieval 'ladies and knights' emphasizing the continuity of the historical record.  No \softline
'humanist' writer would be likely to use such a locution that so dramatically erases the gap \softline
between classical antiquity and the present age.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 72.}{\plain \fs24   For a division of the parts of the canto, following that made by Lanfranco Caretti (}{\plain \fs24 \i Il \softline
canto di Francesca}{\plain \fs24  [Lucca: Lucentia, 1951]) and then expanding it, see Mazzoni ("Il canto V \softline
dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno,}{\plain \fs24 " }{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura Dantis Romana: Letture degli anni 1973-76}{\plain \fs24  [Rome: Bonacci, 1977]), pp. \softline
99-100.  Mazzoni claims that the canto is divided into two precise halves (vv. 1-71; 72-142) and \softline
that these are then divided into seven parallel scenes or moments.  It is surely true that the rest of \softline
the canto -- its second half -- is devoted mainly and essentially to Francesca.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 74.}{\plain \fs24   To be 'light upon the wind' is, to some readers, a sign of Francesca's and Paolo's \softline
noble ability to triumph over their dismal surroundings; to others, it indicates that they are driven \softline
even more wildly than some other shades by the winds of passion.  This first detail begins a \softline
series of challenging phrasings that invite the reader to consider closely the ambiguities of the \softline
entire episode.  For a summary of the issues at stake here, see Mazzoni, "Il canto V dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno,}{\plain \fs24 " \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura Dantis Romana: Letture degli anni 1973-76}{\plain \fs24  (Rome: Bonacci, 1977), pp. 124-28.  And \softline
for a thorough consideration of the history of interpretation of the episode of Francesca see A. E. \softline
Quaglio, 'Francesca' (ED.1971.3), pp. 1-13.  For the background of political intrigue that informs \softline
this episode see Teodolinda Barolini, "Dante and Francesca da Rimini: Realpolitik, Romance, \softline
Gender," }{\plain \fs24 \i Speculum}{\plain \fs24  75 (2000), pp. 1-28.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 76-78.}{\plain \fs24   Virgil's only complete tercet in the second half of the canto (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . \softline
V.111) is laconic, as though he were aware of the emotions felt by Dante (which he himself had \softline
so devastatingly presented in }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  IV, the story of love's destructive power over Dido) and \softline
realized there was nothing he had said or could say that might rein in his excited pupil.  Paola \softline
Marconi ("'per quello amor che i mena': }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V, 78 e il }{\plain \fs24 \i Roman de Tristan}{\plain \fs24  de B{\f1\u233\'e9}roul," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i L{\u8219\'27}Alighieri}{\plain \fs24  20 [2002], pp. 77-93) argues that Dante's depiction of the lovers as being 'led' by love \softline
is rooted in the earliest French versions of }{\plain \fs24 \i Tristan}{\plain \fs24 , which may have circulated in Italy and been \softline
known to Dante.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 80.}{\plain \fs24   The protagonist's adjective for the two sinners (they are 'anime }{\plain \fs24 \i affannate}{\plain \fs24 ') may well \softline
be meant to remind us of the only other time we find that adjective in the first }{\plain \fs24 \i cantica}{\plain \fs24 , at }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  \softline
I.22, when Dante is described as being like a man who has escaped from the sea 'with laboring \softline
breath' (}{\plain \fs24 \i con lena affannata}{\plain \fs24 ).  If that is true, it further binds the character's sense of identity with \softline
these sinners.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 82-84.}{\plain \fs24   The third simile involving birds in this canto (and there are only three similes in \softline
it) compares the two lovers to doves.  As Shoaf, in "Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i colombi}{\plain \fs24  and the Figuralism of Hope \softline
in the }{\plain \fs24 \i Divine Comedy}{\plain \fs24 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24  93 (1975), pp. 27-59, has demonstrated, there is a 'dove \softline
program' in the }{\plain \fs24 \i Comedy}{\plain \fs24 , beginning with the Venereal doves reflected here, passing through the \softline
dove-simile in }{\plain \fs24 \i Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24  II (vv. 124-129), and finishing in the reference to James and Peter as \softline
'doves' of the Holy Spirit in }{\plain \fs24 \i Paradiso}{\plain \fs24  XXV (vv. 19-21).  Dante's nest-seeking doves seem to \softline
reflect both }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  V.213-217 and }{\plain \fs24 \i Georgics}{\plain \fs24  I.414.  A student at Princeton, Daniel Cheely '03, \softline
has recently suggested that another Virgilian passage is echoed here: }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  II.516, the \softline
description of Hecuba and her daughters, huddled together like doves driven before a black \softline
