(Florence: Olschki, 1994 [1989]), pp. 45-48.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 88.}{\plain \fs24   The beginning of Francesca's highly rhetorical speech reflects the tradition of \softline
classical rhetoric that would have a speaker first seek to gain the sympathy of the audience, a \softline
device referred to as }{\plain \fs24 \i captatio benevolentiae}{\plain \fs24 , the capturing of the goodwill of one's auditors.  For \softline
noteworthy earlier examples of }{\plain \fs24 \i captatio}{\plain \fs24  see Beatrice's first words to Virgil (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . II.58-60) and \softline
Virgil's first words to her in return (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . II.76-81).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 91-93.}{\plain \fs24   Francesca's locutions are revealing and instructive: God is portrayed as having \softline
turned away from the two lovers, while Dante is welcomed for not having done so, for feeling \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i piet{\f2 \'42}}{\plain \fs24  for them.  This canto has one of its 'key words' in }{\plain \fs24 \i amore}{\plain \fs24 , which occurs fully eleven times \softline
in it (vv. 61, 66, 69, 78, 100, 103, 106, 119, 125, 128, 134).  But this word, 'pity,' is crucial as \softline
well (vv. 72, 93, 117, 140, and, in the continuing action of the next canto, VI, 2).  Dante is filled \softline
with pity for lost lovers.  Should he be?  That may be the central question facing a reader of \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V (see further discussion, below, in the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.142).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
