}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 97.}{\plain \fs24   For the Italian text with an English translation of Boccaccio's Francesca-favoring \softline
narrative, in his }{\plain \fs24 \i Esposizioni}{\plain \fs24 , see Singleton, comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.97.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 100-106.}{\plain \fs24   The use of anaphora (repetition) here at the beginning of each tercet, 'Amor... \softline
Amor... Amor...,' underlines the rhetorical skill of Francesca, who presses her case with listening 
Dante: it was Love's fault that she and Paolo fell into carnal passion.  'Amor' appears three times \softline
as the first word in a tercet after an end-stopped line and thus must be capitalized.  It seems also \softline
reasonable to believe that Francesca is here referring to her 'god,' the Lord of Love, Cupid, \softline
