}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 102.}{\plain \fs24   Against Pagliaro (}{\plain \fs24 \i Ulisse}{\plain \fs24 : }{\plain \fs24 \i ricerche semantiche sulla "Divina Commedia"}{\plain \fs24  [Messina-Florence: D'Anna, 1967]), pp. 136-49, who argues that Francesca is referring to the way in \softline
which she was made to fall in love, Padoan (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.101) argues persuasively that she \softline
refers in fact to the brutal manner of her death.  This verse is much debated.  Padoan has recently \softline
returned to the argument, reinforcing his claims (}{\plain \fs24 \i Il lungo cammino del "Poema sacro": studi \softline
danteschi}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Olschki, 1993], pp. 189-200).  See also the strong arguments of Chiavacci \softline
Leonardi (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno, con il commento di A. M. C. L. }{\plain \fs24 [Milan: Mondadori, 1991]),  pp. 168-69.  As \softline
much as we may agree with this view of the matter, we must also acknowledge that the wording \softline
of the text allows, in itself, either interpretation.  Our translation therefore leaves the meaning \softline
ambiguous, as does, indeed, the original, whatever Dante's intentions.  Since these words were \softline
written, Lino Pertile ("Il modo di Paolo," in }{\plain \fs24 \i Miscellanea di studi offerta dall'Universit{\f2 \'42} di \softline
Urbino a Claudio Varese per i suoi novantanni}{\plain \fs24 , ed. Giorgio Cerboni Baiardi [Manziana (Rome): \softline
Vecchiarelli Editore, 2001]), pp. 623-33, has produced a response to Padoan's arguments that is \softline
