{\plain \fs24 \tab Petrocchi is harshly polemical against those who have argued that this verse is spoken by \softline
Paolo (}{\plain \fs24 \i La Commedia secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24 ), p. 90.  It is indeed difficult to imagine \softline
that this rhetorically perfect speech could suddenly turn into a 'chorus' without the poet having \softline
given some very clear indication that such was the case.  The next verse, 'These words were borne \softline
from them to us,' does not necessarily mean that they were }{\plain \fs24 \i spoken}{\plain \fs24  by both lovers, only that they \softline
come from where they where, reminding us that we always see them together.  As Benvenuto \softline
(comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.108) and Boccaccio (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.106-108) both insist, Francesca is \softline
speaking for herself }{\plain \fs24 \i and}{\plain \fs24  for Paolo.  However, for a return to the notion that this last line is \softline
spoken, not by Francesca, but by Paolo, see Gorni ("Francesca e Paolo: La voce di lui," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Intersezioni}{\plain \fs24  16 [1996]), pp. 383-90.  It is difficult to accept such a view, since Dante is almost \softline
always carefully precise in separating one speaker's words from another's.  And while punctuation \softline
in the manuscript tradition is not (and cannot be) reliable, it nonetheless seems odd that no one \softline
else had treated the line this way, which in fact seems more ingenious than sensible; that would at \softline
least suggest that, from the beginning, there have been no manscripts that gave the line to \softline
Francesca's lover.  Further, for Paolo to enter the fray in this single (and petulant? [if it is his only \softline
vengeful utterance]) outburst essentially destroys the effect of Francesca's climactic words, \softline
drawing attention from her just before she falls silent.  And it is clear from what follows that it is \softline
she who is much on Dante's mind, not Paolo.  \par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 109-117.}{\plain \fs24   These nine verses contain the 'drama' of the canto }{\plain \fs24 \i in nuce}{\plain \fs24 .  Dante's pensive \softline
condition in the first tercet reflects his being moved deeply by Francesca's beautiful speech; \softline
Virgil attempts to spur him to thoughtful appreciation of what he has seen and heard; the second \softline
tercet records his more emotional than rational outburst: he is totally sympathetic to the lovers, \softline
and now, in the third, he turns to tell Francesca that he is filled with pity for her.  She has won \softline
him over.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Some twenty years ago Dante's tearful state (v. 117) reminded Elizabeth Raymond and \softline
Susan Saltrick (both Princeton '78) of the tears Augustine shed for Dido -- see }{\plain \fs24 \i Confessions}{\plain \fs24  I.13.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 114.}{\plain \fs24   Padoan argues effectively (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.114), against the more widespread \softline
opinion, that the phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i al doloroso passo}{\plain \fs24  (to this woeful pass) refers to spiritual damnation rather \softline
than to physical death.  Chiavacci Leonardi (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno, con il commento di A. M. C. L. }{\plain \fs24 [Milan: \softline
Mondadori, 1991]), p. 160, reproposes the gloss of Francesco da Buti (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.114), \softline
which asserts that the phrase simultaneously recalls their sin, the moment of their death, and their \softline
subsequent damnation.  Padoan's solution seems the more economical and in keeping with the \softline
protagonist's view of the two sinners, here circling forever on the black winds of hell.  The word \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i doloroso}{\plain \fs24  may reflect the }{\plain \fs24 \i dolenti note}{\plain \fs24 , the agonized cries of the damned in this circle (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.25), \softline
as well as look forward to the }{\plain \fs24 \i dolore}{\plain \fs24  of the first verse of Francesca's second speech (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.121), \softline
the sorrow that she now feels in hell remembering her past happiness.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 118-120.}{\plain \fs24   In 1972 Georgia Nugent, then a student at Princeton, pointed out that Dante's \softline
question mimics the questions used by confessors to ascertain the nature of a penitent's sins.  \softline
Here, we may reflect, Dante is behaving more like a priest in the so-called 'religion of Love' than \softline
like a Christian confessor.  See the earlier discussion of confession in this canto, in the note to \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V.8.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 121-126.}{\plain \fs24   'This [the first tercet] imitates Virgil... but literally translates Bo{\f1\u235\'eb}tius' (cited \softline
from J. Taaffe, }{\plain \fs24 \i A Comment on the "Divine Comedy" of Dante Alighieri}{\plain \fs24  [London, John Murray, \softline
1822] p. 326).  See the }{\plain \fs24 \i Consolation of Philosophy}{\plain \fs24  II, pr. 4: 'in omni adversitate fortunae \softline
infelicissimum est genus infortunii fuisse felicem' (among fortune's many adversities the most \softline
unhappy kind is once to have been happy).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab For the Virgilian resonances (}{\plain \fs24 \i Aen}{\plain \fs24 . II.3-13), see the fairly detailed account in Hollander, \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Allegory in Dante{\u8219\'27}s "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24  (Princeton, Princeton University Press, 1969), pp. 110-11.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 123.}{\plain \fs24   There is debate as to whether the word }{\plain \fs24 \i dottore}{\plain \fs24  (here 'teacher') refers to Boethius or \softline
Virgil.  Most prefer the second hypothesis, but see Baldelli, }{\plain \fs24 \i Dante e Francesca}{\plain \fs24  (Ravenna: Longo, \softline
1999), p. 63.  We should realize that either choice forces upon us a somewhat ungainly \softline
hypothesis, the first that Francesca knows Boethius well (it is only several years since Dante had \softline
characterized the }{\plain \fs24 \i Consolation of Philosophy}{\plain \fs24  as a work known only to few [at }{\plain \fs24 \i Convivio}{\plain \fs24  II.xii.2]), \softline
the second that she recognizes the Roman poet Virgil without having had him identified by \softline
Dante.  Since Virgil is referred to by Dante as 'il mio dottore' in this very canto (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.70), and \softline
since we have visited his 'sorrow' a single canto earlier, where we learn what causes the virtuous \softline
pagans their unending unhappiness, it seems the wiser choice to accept the notion that Dante, \softline
taking advantage of poetic license, allows Francesca to recognize Virgil.  \par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 127-128.}{\plain \fs24   Much has been written on the Old French sources of this scene.  Work in \softline
English includes articles by Davy Carozza, "Elements of the }{\plain \fs24 \i roman courtois}{\plain \fs24  in the Episode of \softline
Paolo and Francesca (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V)," }{\plain \fs24 \i Papers on Language and Literature}{\plain \fs24  3 (1967), pp. 291-301, and \softline
Donald Maddox, "The Arthurian Intertexts of }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V," }{\plain \fs24 \i Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24  114 (1996), pp. 113-27.  \softline
And for a possible link to the love story of Eloise and Abelard see Peter Dronke, "Francesca and \softline
H{\f1\u233\'e9}loise," }{\plain \fs24 \i Comparative Literature}{\plain \fs24  27 (1975), pp. 113-35.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 132.}{\plain \fs24   Francesca's account of her and Paolo's conquest by Amor is 'corrected' by a later \softline
text, Dante's reference to God as the 'punto che mi vinse' (}{\plain \fs24 \i Par}{\plain \fs24 . XXX.11), where Dante is, like \softline
Paolo, 'constrained' by love (}{\plain \fs24 \i strinse}{\plain \fs24  [v. 128]; }{\plain \fs24 \i Par. }{\plain \fs24 XXX.15: }{\plain \fs24 \i amor mi costrinse}{\plain \fs24 ) -- but his desire is 
for Beatrice, not for a fleshly liaison.  The passage in }{\plain \fs24 \i Paradiso}{\plain \fs24  is clearly meant to reflect \softline
negatively, not only on the amorous activity of Francesca and Paolo, but on the protagonist's \softline
reactions to it.  The god of Love and Francesca are being played against God and Beatrice -- or so \softline
we will understand once we reach the last }{\plain \fs24 \i cantica}{\plain \fs24 .  For the resonance of this self-citation see \softline
Hollander, "Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i Commedia}{\plain \fs24  and the Classical Tradition: the Case of Virgil," in }{\plain \fs24 \i The "Divine \softline
Comedy" and the Encyclopedia of Arts and Sciences: Acta of the International Dante Symposium, \softline
13-16 November 1983, Hunter College, New York}{\plain \fs24 , ed. G. Di Scipio and A. Scaglione \softline
(Amsterdam: John Benjamins, 1988), pp. 7-8, discussing the contributions of Contini (}{\plain \fs24 \i Un' idea di \softline
Dante}{\plain \fs24  [Turin: Einaudi, 1976]), p. 206; Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i Il Virgilio dantesco: tragedia nella \softline
"Commedia"}{\plain \fs24  [Florence: Olschki, 1983]), pp. 139-40; and Dronke ("Symbolism and Structure in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i Paradiso}{\plain \fs24  30," }{\plain \fs24 \i Romance Philology}{\plain \fs24  43 [1989]), p. 30.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 137.}{\plain \fs24   Once again Francesca blames another for the two lovers' predicament, this time the \softline
go-between in the tale of Lancelot and Guinevere as well as author of the tale.  By now we have \softline
come to see -- or should have -- how often her problems are laid at the doors of others.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 138.}{\plain \fs24   Francesca, reading a book that leads to her 'conversion' to sin and death in the \softline
company of a man named Paul, is the 'negative antitype' of St. Augustine, reading a book by Paul \softline
that leads to his conversion (}{\plain \fs24 \i Confessions}{\plain \fs24  VIII.xii -- see T.K. Swing for what seems to be the first \softline
observation of this striking connection [}{\plain \fs24 \i The Fragile Leaves of the Sibyl}{\plain \fs24  (Westminster: The \softline
Newman Press, 1962)], p. 299, and further discussion by Hollander [}{\plain \fs24 \i Allegory in Dante{\u8219\'27}s \softline
"Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 ], pp. 112-13).  Augustine is converted by reading a passage in St. Paul (Romans \softline
13:13-14): 'Let us walk honestly as in the day; not in rioting and drunkenness, not in chambering \softline
and wantonness, not in strife and envying.  But put you on the Lord Jesus Christ, and make not \softline
provision for the flesh, to fulfill the lusts thereof.'  Here, we may reflect, Francesca reads a book \softline
and is 'converted,' by doing so, to the lust that leads to death.  And if Augustine was converted by \softline
reading a man named Paul, Francesca gives herself to adultery with a man bearing the same \softline
name.  As Swing has pointed out, Francesca's last words, }{\plain \fs24 \i quel giorno pi{\f2 \'6a} non vi leggemmo avante}{\plain \fs24  \softline
(that day we read in it no further), seem more than coincidentally close to Augustine's }{\plain \fs24 \i nec ultra \softline
volui legere}{\plain \fs24  (and I did not wish to read any further).  For support of the idea that Dante is here \softline
thinking of this pivotal moment in Augustine's spiritual autobiography, see John A. Scott, \softline
"Dante's Francesca and the Poet's Attitude toward Courtly Literature," }{\plain \fs24 \i Reading Medieval Studies}{\plain \fs24  \softline
5 (1979), p. 14.  A recent study of the presence of Augustine in Dante does not deal with the \softline
question; see Selene Sarteschi ( "Sant'Agostino in Dante e nell'et{\f2 \'42} di Dante," in her }{\plain \fs24 \i Per la \softline
"Commedia" e non per essa soltanto}{\plain \fs24  [Rome: Bulzoni, 2002 (1999)], pp. 171-94).  If we are meant \softline
to think of Augustine's book here, that would round off this canto's concern with confession (see \softline
discussion, above, in the notes to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.8 and V.118-120).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 140.}{\plain \fs24   We now realize that during the entire episode we have not heard a word from Paolo.  \softline
Dante will return to this strategy when he twice again involves pairs of sinners in suffering \softline
together, Diomedes with Ulysses in }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  XXVI, Ruggieri with Ugolino in }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  XXXIII.  In \softline
each case one of the two is a silent partner.  We can try to imagine what an eternity of silence in \softline
the company of the voluble being who shares the culpability for one's damnation might be like.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Petrocchi (}{\plain \fs24 \i La Commedia secondo l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 , }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24 ), p. 94, defends breaking the \softline
line where he does (after }{\plain \fs24 \i piang{\f1\u235\'eb}a}{\plain \fs24  and not, as in the 1921 edition, after }{\plain \fs24 \i s{\f2 \'58}}{\plain \fs24 ), because that \softline
punctuation would make it seem that Dante wept only for Paolo's plight, and not for the condition 
of both the lovers.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 141.}{\plain \fs24   Dante's death-like swoon has him experiencing something akin to the death in \softline
sensuality experienced by Francesca and Paolo.  This is to be at odds with the view of Pietrobono \softline
(comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.142), who argues that Dante's death-like collapse mirrors his attaining of the \softline
state urged by Paul in his Epistle to the Romans, chapter 6, wherein the Christian 'dies' to sin in \softline
imitation of Christ (e.g.,'For he that is dead is freed from sin' -- Romans 6:7).  It would rather \softline
seem that this is exactly }{\plain \fs24 \i not}{\plain \fs24  the state attained by the protagonist at this point in the poem.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Donald Maddox ("The Arthurian Intertexts of }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V," }{\plain \fs24 \i Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24  114 [1996]), pp. \softline
119-22, draws a parallel between Dante's fainting spell and that suffered by Galehot in the prose \softline
Lancelot.  For the OF prose version consulted by Dante, see Paget Toynbee, 'Dante and the \softline
Lancelot Romance,' in his }{\plain \fs24 \i Dante Studies and Researches}{\plain \fs24  (Port Washington, NY: Kennikat Press, \softline
1971 [1902]), pp. 1-37.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 142.}{\plain \fs24   Torraca (comm. on }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.142) was perhaps the first commentator to note the \softline
Arthurian material that lies behind Dante's famous line: the Italian prose version of the stories of \softline
Arthur's court, }{\plain \fs24 \i La tavola ritonda}{\plain \fs24 , XLVII, where Tristan's response to Isolde's death is described \softline
as follows: 'e cadde s{\f2 \'58} come corpo morto.'  The protagonist is thus compared to the victim of \softline
overwhelming passion.  His fainting marks him here as unable to control his pity, as it had had \softline
the same effect with respect to fear two cantos earlier (}{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . III.136).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab The fifth canto of }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  is the cause of continuing debate.  Where are we to locate \softline
ourselves as witnesses to these scenes?  Romantic readers understandably tend to align \softline
themselves with the love that Francesca emblematizes and/or the pity that Dante exhibits; \softline
moralizing ones with the firmness that an Augustinian reader would feel.  Virgil perhaps, given \softline
his silence through most of the second half of the canto (once Francesca appears on the scene he \softline
speaks only two words: 'che pense?' [what are your thoughts? -- }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.111]), would then seem to \softline
be trying to rein in Dante's enthusiastic involvement with this enticing shade.  Yet even as \softline
theologically-oriented a reader as Mazzoni ("Il canto V dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno,}{\plain \fs24 " }{\plain \fs24 \i Lectura Dantis Romana: \softline
Letture degli anni 1973-76}{\plain \fs24  [Rome: Bonacci, 1977], pp. 125-26) finds it important to distance \softline
himself from such 'rigid moralizing' as is found in Giovanni Busnelli, "La ruina del secondo \softline
cerchio e Francesca da Rimini," }{\plain \fs24 \i Miscellanea Dantesca pubblicata a cura del Comitato cattolico \softline
padovano per il VI centenario della morte del Poeta}{\plain \fs24  [Padua, 1922], pp. 49-60, and in Rocco \softline
Montano, }{\plain \fs24 \i Storia della poesia di Dante}{\plain \fs24 , vol. I (Naples: Quaderni di Delta, 1962).  A view similar \softline
to Mazzoni's is found in a much-cited essay by Renato Poggioli: 'The "romance" of Paolo and \softline
Francesca becomes in Dante's hands an "antiromance," or rather, both things at once.  As such, it \softline
is able to express and to judge romantic love at the same time' ("Tragedy or Romance? A Reading \softline
of the Paolo and Francesca Episode in Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i PMLA}{\plain \fs24  72 [1957], p. 358).  In America, \softline
the role of the 'rigid moralizer' has been played, in recent times, most notably by Anthony Cassell \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i Dante's Fearful Art of Justice}{\plain \fs24  [Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1984]), with similar \softline
responses from most of his reviewers.  For Mazzoni and many, perhaps most, contemporary \softline
readers, the canto needs to be responded to more generously than the 'moralizers' would like.  \softline
And, to be sure, there is at times a certain perhaps unfortunately zealous tone in the words of such \softline
critics.  On the other hand, their views seem only to accord with the overall aims of the poet and \softline
his poem.  Francesca is, after all, in hell.  The love she shares with Paolo was and is a 'mad love' \softline
(for this concept see Silvio Avalle d'Arco, "... de fole amor," in }{\plain \fs24 \i Modelli semiologici nella \softline
"Commedia" di Dante}{\plain \fs24  [Milan: Bompiani, 1975]), pp. 97-121; 137-73.  And so, where some 
would find pity the middle ground for the reader to occupy, between the sinful lust of Francesca \softline
and Paolo and the 'rigid moralizers,' others, including this commentator, argue that it is pity itself \softline
that is here at fault.  }{\plain \fs24 \i Amore}{\plain \fs24  and }{\plain \fs24 \i piet{\f2 \'42}}{\plain \fs24  are no doubt among the 'key words' of the canto (see above, \softline
the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . V.91-93); that does not mean that they must function in opposition to one another.  \softline
They may be versions of the same emotion.  Indeed, if we see that Francesca's aim is precisely to \softline
gain Dante's pity, and that she is successful in doing so, we perhaps ought to question his offering \softline
of it.  Sympathy for the damned, in the }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24 , is nearly always and nearly certainly the sign of a \softline
wavering moral disposition.  To cite again the words of Guido da Pisa (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i Inf}{\plain \fs24 . XX.28-30), \softline
'the time for mercy is here in this world, while in the world to come it is time only for justice.'  \softline
That is a standard Christian medieval view.  Twenty-first-century readers should probably keep it \softline
in mind.  However, for a strong attack on such readings, one which argues for the notion that, in \softline
all his works, Dante accepts the ineluctable force of passionate love, see Ignazio Baldelli, }{\plain \fs24 \i Dante e \softline
Francesca}{\plain \fs24  (Ravenna: Longo, 1999), esp. pp. 66-67, 73-87.  For a more balanced evaluation of \softline
this fundamental problem in the interpretation of Dante's view of carnal affection, see Claudia \softline
Villa ("Tra affetto e piet{\f2 \'42}: per }{\plain \fs24 \i Inferno}{\plain \fs24  V," }{\plain \fs24 \i Lettere Italiane}{\plain \fs24  51 [1999]), pp. 513-41.\par
